.TH "TEMPORAL.ZONEDDATETIME.STARTOFDAY" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.startOfDay \-
Temporal.ZonedDateTime.prototype.startOfDay()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]startOfDay()\f[B]\f[R] method of
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] instances returns a
\f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object representing the first instant
of this date in the time zone.
It usually has a time of \f[CR]00:00:00\f[R], but may be different if
the midnight doesn\(cqt exist due to offset changes, in which case the
first time that exists is returned.
.PP
It is equivalent to calling \f[CR]withPlainTime()\f[R] with no
arguments.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
startOfDay()
.EE
.SS Parameters
None.
.SS Return value
A \f[CR]Temporal.ZonedDateTime\f[R] object with instant \f[CR]t\f[R],
such that:
.IP \(bu 2
The date at \f[CR]t\f[R] is different from the date one nanosecond
before \f[CR]t\f[R].
.IP \(bu 2
The date at \f[CR]t\f[R] is the same as the date of \f[CR]this\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using startOfDay()
.IP
.EX
\f[I]// In the US, DST transitions happen at 2am, so the midnight exists\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2024\-03\-10T12:00:00\-04:00[America/New_York]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt.startOfDay().toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2024\-03\-10T00:00:00\-05:00[America/New_York]\(dq\f[R]

\f[I]// In Brazil, DST transitions happened at midnight, so the midnight didn\(aqt exist\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] dt2 = Temporal.ZonedDateTime.from(
  \(dq2015\-10\-18T12:00\-02:00[America/Sao_Paulo]\(dq,
);
console.log(dt2.startOfDay().toString()); \f[I]// \(dq2015\-10\-18T01:00:00\-02:00[America/Sao_Paulo]\(dq\f[R]
.EE
